{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569282"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:25:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:25:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21984"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21984"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.73,0.03,0.06,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14944"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105934"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14944"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21984"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88409"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2047"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4088"},{"type":"tags","id":"4173"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"5018"},{"type":"tags","id":"9644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11990"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"38902"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38903"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43755"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105934","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105934"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for a follow up appointment with a three-month history of heavy menstrual bleeding. She has been trying to conceive for the past six months with her partner. She has no significant medical history and takes oral iron tablets daily, which were commenced two months ago for iron deficiency anaemia. She does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe experiences menstrual bleeding for seven days every 26 days, with very heavy flow requiring hourly pad changes on the first three days and notes that she passes small clots at times. She recalls her periods being heavy in her teens however had a Mirena intrauterine device (IUD) inserted at age 18 for dysfunctional uterine bleeding with good clinical effect. She had her IUD replaced at five yearly intervals since then, with IUD removal six months ago. She denies intermenstrual bleeding, postcoital bleeding, or pelvic pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable and pelvic examination reveals a normal-sized uterus with no adnexal masses.  Investigations ordered last week show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 118 g/L (125-160)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMCV 82 fL (80-96)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFerritin 25 \u03bcg/L (15-200)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPelvic ultrasound: normal uterus and ovaries with an endometrial thickness of 8 mm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment for her heavy menstrual bleeding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Combined oral contraceptive pill","Tranexamic acid","Drospirenone","Mefenamic acid","Norethisterone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with heavy menstrual bleeding while actively trying to conceive, which requires careful consideration of treatment options that will not interfere with fertility or pregnancy. The key is selecting a non-hormonal treatment that effectively reduces menstrual blood loss without affecting ovulation or conception.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranexamic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice as it is a non-hormonal antifibrinolytic agent that reduces menstrual blood loss by 40-50% without affecting ovulation or fertility. It works by inhibiting plasminogen activation, thereby reducing clot breakdown and menstrual flow. It can be taken cyclically during menstruation (typically 1g three times daily for up to five days) and is safe for use when trying to conceive and during early pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombined oral contraceptive pill\u003C/strong\u003E would be highly effective for reducing heavy menstrual bleeding but is contraindicated in women actively trying to conceive as it prevents ovulation. It would be an excellent option once family planning is complete.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrospirenone\u003C/strong\u003E is a progestogen used in some combined oral contraceptive pills as well as a progestogen only pill. It would prevent ovulation and therefore conception, making it inappropriate for a woman trying to conceive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMefenamic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug that can reduce menstrual blood loss by 20-30%. While it doesn\u0027t prevent conception, there are concerns about its use in early pregnancy, particularly around the time of implantation and in the first trimester, making it less ideal for women actively trying to conceive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENorethisterone\u003C/strong\u003E is a synthetic progestogen that can be used to reduce heavy menstrual bleeding. However it may interfere with normal ovulation patterns and is not recommended for women trying to conceive. It is an important practice point to distinguish between the doses of norethisterone for heavy menstrual bleeding management, to delay menstruation, and that for contraception. Additionally, there are potential concerns about exposure during early pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient should be counselled about taking tranexamic acid during menstruation only. Follow-up should be arranged to assess treatment response and to consider further investigation if bleeding remains problematic despite treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Tranexamic acid is safe and effective for reducing heavy menstrual bleeding in women trying to conceive.","Tranexamic acid reduces menstrual blood loss by 40-50% and can be used cyclically during menstruation."],"references":["Percy L, Mansour D, Fraser I. Iron deficiency and iron deficiency anaemia in women. Best Practice \u0026 Research Clinical Obstetrics \u0026 Gynaecology. 2017;40:55-67. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28029503/","Peitsidis P, Kadir RA. Antifibrinolytic therapy with tranexamic acid in pregnancy and postpartum. 2011. In: Database of Abstracts of Reviews of Effects (DARE): Quality-assessed Reviews [Internet]. York (UK): Centre for Reviews and Dissemination (UK); 1995-. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK80933/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88409"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21984"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88409"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-14T21:38:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-14T21:41:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14944"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105934"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"de